    "description": "A structured framework for comparing generative engine optimisation tools across consistent evaluation dimensions — platform coverage, citation tracking accuracy, schema support, reporting, price model, and integrations.",
    "url": "https://geooptimised.com/geo-tools-comparison/",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-07",
    "dateModified": "2026-06-07",
    "inLanguage": "en-GB",
    "image": "https://geooptimised.com/og-image.png",
    "mainEntityOfPage": {
      "@type": "WebPage",
      "@id": "https://geooptimised.com/geo-tools-comparison/"
    },
    "author": {
      "@id": "https://geooptimised.com/#organization"
    },
    "publisher": {
      "@id": "https://geooptimised.com/#organization"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What dimensions should I use to compare GEO tools?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The six most important dimensions for a structured GEO tools comparison are: platform coverage (which AI engines the tool monitors), citation tracking accuracy (whether it captures URL-level citations and response context), schema and structured-data support (whether it flags gaps in your markup), reporting quality (trend views, competitive benchmarks, exportability), pricing model (flat subscription versus per-query), and integrations (connections to analytics, CRM, or SEO platforms you already use). Weighting these dimensions according to your programme's current maturity will produce a more defensible selection decision than relying on a single vendor score."
        }
