    <div class="lg:col-span-9 prose-dark space-y-16">

      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="why-comparison-matters" class="anchor-top">
        <h2>Why a Consistent Comparison Framework Matters</h2>
        <p><strong>The single biggest mistake buyers make when evaluating GEO tools is comparing them on incomparable terms.</strong> One vendor leads with platform count, another with citation accuracy, a third with price, and a fourth with a feature list that conflates measurement and optimisation capabilities. Without a consistent framework applied to every tool under consideration, you end up buying on the basis of the dimension the vendor chose to emphasise rather than the dimension your programme most needs.</p>
        <p>This is not a problem unique to GEO tools. It exists in every young software category where terminology is not yet standardised and buyers lack the domain experience to probe beneath marketing language. The GEO tool market is young — the category barely existed before 2023 — and terminology is still settling. "AI visibility tracking", "LLM citation monitoring", "generative search optimisation", and "answer engine tracking" are used to describe overlapping but distinct capabilities depending on the vendor.</p>
        <p>A comparison framework solves this by defining the dimensions in advance, specifying what strong, adequate, and weak performance looks like on each one, and applying those definitions consistently across every tool you evaluate. The six dimensions described below are the ones that practitioners at <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO programmes</a> have found most predictive of whether a tool genuinely advances their measurement capability. They are not the only dimensions that matter, but they cover the core of what separates useful tools from superficially impressive ones.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="six-dimensions" class="anchor-top">
        <h2>The Six Comparison Dimensions</h2>

        <h3 id="dimension-platform-coverage" class="mt-8 font-display text-xl font-semibold text-ink-100">1. Platform Coverage</h3>
        <p><strong>Platform coverage determines how representative your AI visibility data actually is.</strong> A tool that monitors only one or two AI platforms will produce a systematically distorted picture of your brand's citation position. The minimum credible set for a meaningful <a href="/geo-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO tool</a> in 2026 is ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google Gemini, and Microsoft Copilot. Beyond that minimum, useful additions include Google AI Overviews (structurally different from Gemini standalone), Claude, and the ability to run custom prompt libraries rather than pre-set generic queries.</p>
        <p>Platform coverage also extends to geographic and language variants. A brand operating in multiple markets needs to know whether its citation rate differs between the UK, US, and Australian instances of the same AI platform — answers can and do vary by locale. Tools that allow locale-specific querying provide considerably more actionable data for international programmes.</p>

        <h3 id="dimension-citation-tracking" class="mt-8 font-display text-xl font-semibold text-ink-100">2. Citation Tracking Accuracy</h3>
        <p><strong>Citation tracking accuracy is the dimension that most directly separates useful tools from vanity-metric dashboards.</strong> A tool that tells you only whether your brand name appeared in an AI response is providing information, not intelligence. The questions that drive optimisation decisions are: which specific URL was cited; where in the response did the citation appear; was the citation a direct attribution, a paraphrase, or an incidental mention; and is the description of your brand accurate?</p>
        <p>URL-level citation tracking is particularly valuable because it reveals which pages in your content estate are functioning as AI citation sources. This information directly informs content investment decisions: pages that earn citations warrant further development, and pages that rank well in traditional search but earn no AI citations may need structural changes to their headings, definitions, or schema markup. Without URL-level data, you cannot draw that distinction.</p>

        <h3 id="dimension-schema-support" class="mt-8 font-display text-xl font-semibold text-ink-100">3. Schema &amp; Structured-Data Support</h3>
        <p><strong>Structured data reduces ambiguity for AI models, and tools that audit your schema markup surface a class of citation barriers that pure visibility trackers miss.</strong> When an AI model encounters a page with correctly implemented Article, FAQPage, or HowTo schema, it has explicit signals about the content type, the entities involved, and the relationships between them. Pages with incomplete or absent structured data rely on the model's inference — a less reliable path to accurate citation.</p>
        <p>A tool that audits your schema implementation — identifying missing types, flagging syntax errors, and recommending additional markup for high-value pages — provides GEO-specific value that a generic technical SEO crawler does not. The comparison criterion here is not whether a tool has any schema-related feature, but whether its schema analysis is tuned to GEO outcomes (entity clarity, FAQ and definition markup) rather than just generic SEO validity.</p>

        <h3 id="dimension-reporting" class="mt-8 font-display text-xl font-semibold text-ink-100">4. Reporting &amp; Trend Analysis</h3>
        <p><strong>Reporting quality determines whether a tool supports strategic decision-making or only tactical spot-checks.</strong> Current-state data — your citation rate today — has limited value without historical context. AI platform behaviour changes as models are updated, retrieval systems are revised, and the competitive landscape shifts. A tool that only shows current data cannot distinguish between a citation rate change caused by your optimisation work and one caused by a platform-level model update. Historical data retention of at minimum ninety days, and preferably twelve months, is the baseline for credible trend analysis.</p>
        <p>Competitive benchmarking within the reporting layer is the second critical component. Knowing your citation rate in isolation tells you less than knowing how it compares to two or three named competitors for the same query set. This relative context is what allows you to prioritise: if your rate is lower than competitors for a specific topic cluster, that gap represents a measurable opportunity.</p>

        <h3 id="dimension-pricing" class="mt-8 font-display text-xl font-semibold text-ink-100">5. Pricing Model</h3>
        <p><strong>The pricing model matters as much as the headline price, because per-query billing creates cost uncertainty that caps programme ambition.</strong> Meaningful AI visibility measurement requires running many prompts across multiple platforms at regular intervals — daily or weekly tracking across a prompt library of fifty to two hundred queries is not unusual for a serious programme. A tool that charges per API call will see its costs scale linearly with that volume. What appears affordable at a starter prompt set becomes prohibitively expensive at the scale needed for statistical confidence.</p>
        <p>Flat-subscription models with clearly defined query allowances and transparent overage pricing give programmes the cost predictability they need to commit to a measurement frequency and stick to it. When evaluating pricing, always model the cost at the query volume your programme will <em>actually</em> run — not the volume you might start with in the first month.</p>

        <h3 id="dimension-integrations" class="mt-8 font-display text-xl font-semibold text-ink-100">6. Integrations</h3>
        <p><strong>Integrations determine whether GEO insights flow into the workflows where they can change decisions.</strong> A tool whose data lives entirely within its own dashboard faces a fundamental adoption problem: the people who need to act on citation insights — content writers, editors, SEO managers, CMOs — are unlikely to log in to a separate platform to retrieve them. The best integrations connect the GEO tool to the infrastructure teams already use: GA4 or Looker Studio for analytics, Search Console for traditional search correlation, and the SEO platforms (such as <a href="/semrush-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">SEMrush</a> or <a href="/ahrefs-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Ahrefs</a>) where the broader content and authority strategy lives.</p>
        <p>API access and webhook support are the integration ceiling: they allow you to build custom pipelines that route citation data to your data warehouse, your CMS, or your internal dashboards. Evaluate integrations not by count but by whether they unlock the specific workflow handoffs your programme requires.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: Comparison Table -->
      <section id="criteria-table" class="anchor-top">
        <h2>Comparison-Criteria Table</h2>
        <p><strong>Apply this table directly to any GEO tool you are evaluating.</strong> For each dimension, assess the tool against the three-level descriptors and record your assessment. A tool that scores "Strong" across all six dimensions does not exist — every platform has trade-offs. The goal is a clear-eyed view of where each tool excels and where it requires supplementary capability.</p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-8 rounded-xl border border-[var(--line)]">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)] bg-geo-900">
                <th scope="col" class="py-4 px-5 text-left font-display font-semibold text-ink-100 w-40">Dimension</th>
                <th scope="col" class="py-4 px-5 text-left font-display font-semibold text-accent-400">Strong</th>
                <th scope="col" class="py-4 px-5 text-left font-display font-semibold text-ink-300">Adequate</th>
                <th scope="col" class="py-4 px-5 text-left font-display font-semibold text-ink-500">Weak</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
              {criteria.map((row, i) => (
                <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-geo-950' : 'bg-geo-900/40'}>
                  <td class="py-4 px-5 font-semibold text-ink-100 align-top">
                    {row.label}
                    <p class="mt-1 text-xs font-normal text-ink-500 leading-relaxed">{row.why}</p>
                  </td>
                  <td class="py-4 px-5 text-ink-300 align-top leading-relaxed">{row.strong}</td>
                  <td class="py-4 px-5 text-ink-400 align-top leading-relaxed">{row.adequate}</td>
                  <td class="py-4 px-5 text-ink-500 align-top leading-relaxed">{row.weak}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-5 text-sm text-ink-500 leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-ink-400">Market note:</strong> The GEO tool market is evolving rapidly. Features described here reflect capabilities available as of mid-2026. Verify current functionality and pricing directly with each vendor before making a purchasing decision — capability gaps can close quickly in a young category.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="weighting-dimensions" class="anchor-top">
        <h2>Weighting Dimensions by Programme Stage</h2>
        <p><strong>The relative importance of each dimension changes as a GEO programme matures.</strong> A uniform weighting applied to all six dimensions will steer early-stage programmes towards tools that are more sophisticated than their current measurement process can use. It will also steer mature programmes towards tools that are too simple to support the depth of analysis their reporting stakeholders expect.</p>

        <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <div class="card p-6 border-t-2 border-t-[var(--accent)]">
            <span class="eyebrow">Stage 1</span>
            <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Baseline Measurement</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">No prior GEO data. Primary objective: understand current citation position across the AI landscape.</p>
            <ul class="mt-4 space-y-1 text-sm text-ink-400">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-[var(--accent)] mt-0.5" aria-hidden="true">&#8594;</span> Prioritise: Platform coverage, Pricing model</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-ink-600 mt-0.5" aria-hidden="true">&#8594;</span> Defer: Integrations, Advanced reporting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6 border-t-2 border-t-[var(--accent)]">
            <span class="eyebrow">Stage 2</span>
            <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-50">Active Optimisation</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Baseline established. Ongoing content and entity work underway. Need to measure programme impact.</p>
